n rebellion over police violence against Black people, the Aunties supported and supplied Black Lives Matter protesters and organizations serving Black communities. Providing hundreds of thousands of homemade masks met an urgent public health need and expressed solidarity, care, and political action in a moment of social upheaval. The Auntie Sewing Squad is a quirky, fast-moving, and adaptive mutual-aid group that showed up to meet a critical need. Led primarily by women of color, the group includes some who learned to sew from mothers and grandmothers working for sweatshops or as a survival skill passed down by refugee relatives. The Auntie Sewing Squad speaks back to the history of exploited immigrant labor as it enacts an intersectional commitment to public health for all. This collection of essays and ephemera is a community document of the labor and care of the Auntie Sewing Squad.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCOVID-19 (Disease)xPrevention. 0aCOVID-19 (Disease)xSocial aspects. 0aSocial movementszUnited Statesy21st century. 7aHISTORY / Women .2bisacsh  a2020 history.  aanti asian hate.  ablack lives matter.  abooks for activists.  acovid 19.  ahow to help out.  aintersectional feminism.  ajoin the movement.  amasks.  amutual aid.  apandemic.  asocial justice.  asolidarity.  avolunteering ideas.1 aApeles, Dominie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aApeles, Teena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArana, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBear, Badly Licked, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernadel, Laurie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByun, Joni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul